04065nam a22005775i 9780773561410DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19881988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735614107 a10.1515/97807735614102doi  a(DE-B1597)655555  a(OCoLC)732600631  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD7305.A3bM54 1988eb 7aSCI0300002bisacsh04a363.5/09711 aMiron, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHousing in Postwar Canada :bDemographic Change, Household Formation, and Housing Demand /cJohn R. Miron. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1988] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tDefinitions and Concepts -- tPostwar Patterns of Family Formation -- tPostwar Household Formation -- tAnalysis of Household Formation -- tIncome and Household Formation -- tThe Postwar Housing Stock -- tProsperity and Housing Afforda -- tPublic Policy and Housing Supply -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe size of Canadian households has been declining since at least the 1880s. Miron compares this trend to patterns of household size in England and the United States and argues that postwar changes in household formation in Canada were the result of several forces including the postwar baby boom, increased longevity, changes in marriage pattern, rising incidence of divorce, increased household affluence, and new forms of government assistance to housing. While aggregate growth in population, families, and households helps to explain why more housing was necessary, it does not explain changes in the kind of houses desired. Miron discusses changes in available housing stock as well as changes in structural type such as the great apartment boom of the late 1960s and the re-emergence of owner occupancy in the late 1970s. The types of data available for measuring change in the stock and sources of error in housing data are also analyzed. One of the books most important contributions is an annotated synthesis of national trends in household formation and housing demand, derived from Statistics Canada census data, and accompanied by an insightful analysis of the relation of these trends to housing stock evolution. This is the only available detailed study of these topics in the Canadian context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHouseholdsxCanada. 0aHouseholdszCanada. 0aHousingxCanada. 0aHousingzCanada. 0aLogementxCanada. 0aMénages (Statistique)xCanada. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356141040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561410/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles